Note that, in the KM1 and KM2 measurements the null hypothesis is rejected on the significance level 0.1.

So, there is evidence that the data tested are not normally distributed on the significance level 0.1.

Shapiro-Wilk variance test for normality

After a study is completed, the investigator uses statistical tests to try to reject the null hypothesis in favor of its alternative (much in the same way that a prosecuting attorney tries to convince a judge to reject innocence in favor of guilt).
Source: Hypothesis testing, type I and type II errors

The probability of committing a type I error, rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true, is called (alpha). The other name for this is the level of statistical significance.

The probability of making a type II error, failing to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false is called (beta).

The null-hypothesis (hipoteza zerowa, \(H_0\)) of the ShapiroWilk test is that the data came from a normally distributed variable.

  1. Thus, if the \(p\hbox{-value} < \alpha\), then the null hypothesis is rejected and there is evidence that the data tested are not normally distributed.

  2. On the other hand, if the \(p\hbox{-value} > \alpha\), then the null hypothesis (the sample came from a normally distributed population) can not be rejected.

Establishing, in advance, the maximum chances of errors

The investigator establishes the maximum chance of making type I and type II errors in advance of the study.

Nam zaley, aby bd pierwszego rodzaju (type I) by nieduy (odrzucenie hipotezy zerowej, kiedy jest ona w rzeczywistoci prawdziwa). Bd ten nazywamy (alpha, the level of statistical significance).

Dla naszych danych o liczebnoci prby \(n = 15\) wybieramy significance level (poziom istotnoci) \(\alpha = 0{}1\).

Przykadowe rachunki w R

sort(sat_km1_km2$Y)
##  [1] -1.26325 -0.32240 -0.25886 -0.18975 -0.15886 -0.13575 -0.11200 -0.04325
##  [9] -0.01267  0.00000  0.10575  0.30125  0.44250  0.86689  1.88622
shapiro.test(sat_km1_km2$Y)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sat_km1_km2$Y
## W = 0.85, p-value = 0.02

Poniewa policzone \(p\hbox{-value} = 0{}09\) jest mniejsze od \(\alpha = 0{}1\), wic odrzucamy hipotez zerow, czyli e dane maj rozkad normalny na poziomie istotnoci \(0{}1\).

Jeli pominiemy w danych sat_km1_km2$Y trzy wartoci nietypowe (outliers), pierwsz i dwie ostatnie, to wynikiem testu bdzie:

new_sat_table
##  [1] -0.32240 -0.25886 -0.18975 -0.15886 -0.13575 -0.11200 -0.04325 -0.01267
##  [9]  0.00000  0.10575  0.30125  0.44250
shapiro.test(new_sat_table)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  new_sat_table
## W = 0.92, p-value = 0.3

Tym razem na poziomie istotnoci \(0{}1\) nie podstaw do odrzucenia hipotezy, e dane pochodz z prby o rozkadzie normalnym.

Podsumowanie

  1. Jeli \(p\hbox{-value} < \alpha\), to na danym poziomie istotnoci \(\alpha\) odrzucamy hipotez zerow.

  2. Jeli \(p\hbox{-value} > \alpha\), to na danym poziomie istotnoci \(\alpha\) nie ma podstaw do odrzucenia hipotezy zerowej.
